window.BLS_DATA = {"manifest":{"id":"bls","title":"BLS — Basic Life Support","subtitle":"The Ultimate Provider Course Reviewer","version":"1.0.0","edition":"Based on the AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC","description":"A comprehensive, self-contained study reviewer for Basic Life Support. Each chapter includes a concise summary, clinical pearls, red flags, common mistakes, memory aids, decision trees, high-yield flashcards, AHA-style quiz questions, and realistic scenarios. Designed for EMTs, nurses, nursing students, paramedics, and all healthcare providers preparing for BLS Provider certification.","icon":"heart-pulse","color":"#c8102e","accentColor":"#1f6feb","estimatedHours":12,"difficulty":"Beginner to Intermediate","certification":"AHA BLS Provider","examLink":"https://cpr.heart.org/","audience":["EMT","AEMT","Paramedic","Nurse","Nursing Student","Physician","Healthcare Provider"],"prerequisites":["None — BLS is the entry-level resuscitation course"],"contentTypes":["summary","flashcards","quizzes","scenarios","algorithms","tables"],"chapters":[{"id":"c01","number":1,"title":"Chain of Survival & Systems of Care","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c02","number":2,"title":"Scene Safety, Assessment & Recognition of Cardiac Arrest","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c03","number":3,"title":"High-Quality CPR: Adult (1-Rescuer)","section":"Adult BLS","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c04","number":4,"title":"Adult 2-Rescuer CPR & Team Dynamics","section":"Adult BLS","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c05","number":5,"title":"Automated External Defibrillation (AED)","section":"Adult BLS","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c06","number":6,"title":"Ventilation: Barrier Devices, Pocket Mask & Bag-Mask","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c07","number":7,"title":"Breaths, Ventilations & Advanced Airway Considerations","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c08","number":8,"title":"Child BLS","section":"Pediatric BLS","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c09","number":9,"title":"Infant BLS","section":"Pediatric BLS","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c10","number":10,"title":"Foreign-Body Airway Obstruction (Adult, Child, Infant)","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c11","number":11,"title":"Opioid-Associated Life-Threatening Emergencies","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c12","number":12,"title":"Special Circumstances: Drowning, Pregnancy, Recovery & Post-Arrest Care","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Intermediate"}]},"chapters":{"c01":{"id":"c01","title":"Chain of Survival & Systems of Care","shortTitle":"Chain of Survival","estimatedStudyTime":25,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Describe the purpose of the Chain of Survival and how each link contributes to survival from cardiac arrest.","List the links of the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival and explain why the concept was consolidated.","Differentiate the emphasis of out-of-hospital cardiac arrest (OHCA) from in-hospital cardiac arrest (IHCA).","Explain the role of the recovery link and survivorship after cardiac arrest.","Describe how a BLS provider fits into the larger system of care, including dispatcher-assisted CPR and hand-off to advanced providers.","Explain why early, high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation are the two links most influenced by bystanders and BLS providers."],"summary":[{"title":"What the Chain of Survival Is","content":"The Chain of Survival is a metaphor describing the sequence of time-sensitive actions that give a person in cardiac arrest the best chance of survival. Each link depends on the ones before it: a delay or weakness in any single link reduces the effectiveness of the whole chain. BLS providers own the earliest and most impactful links — recognition, activation, high-quality CPR, and defibrillation."},{"title":"The 2025 Universal Chain of Survival","content":"The 2025 AHA Guidelines consolidated the previously separate adult and pediatric, in-hospital and out-of-hospital chains into a single universal six-link Chain of Survival. The links are: (1) activation of the emergency response, (2) high-quality CPR, (3) defibrillation, (4) advanced resuscitation interventions, (5) post-cardiac arrest care, and (6) recovery. A separate Neonatal Chain of Care was introduced for the newborn population."},{"title":"OHCA vs IHCA Emphasis","content":"Although the chain is now universal, the setting changes where the emphasis falls. Out-of-hospital cardiac arrest depends heavily on bystanders: recognizing arrest, calling for help, starting compressions, and using a public AED before EMS arrives. In-hospital cardiac arrest emphasizes surveillance and prevention — monitoring, rapid-response systems, and early recognition of deterioration — so that many arrests are prevented before they happen."},{"title":"The Recovery Link and Survivorship","content":"Recovery recognizes that survival does not end when a pulse returns. Survivors and their families may face physical, cognitive, and emotional challenges. The recovery link includes rehabilitation, treatment planning, psychological support, and expectations for return to daily life. It reframes cardiac arrest as a condition people survive and live beyond, not merely an event to be reversed."},{"title":"Systems of Care and the BLS Provider's Place","content":"A system of care links people, training, equipment, and organizations so that the chain functions reliably. Dispatchers coach bystanders through compressions (dispatcher-assisted CPR), BLS providers deliver high-quality CPR and defibrillation, and advanced providers add airway management, medications, and post-arrest care. Smooth hand-offs and continuous quality improvement — measuring performance and feeding it back — keep the system strong."}],"clinicalPearls":["Bystander CPR and early defibrillation are the two interventions most strongly associated with survival — and both fall squarely within BLS scope.","For every minute that defibrillation is delayed in a shockable arrest, the probability of survival falls substantially, which is why public-access AEDs matter.","Dispatcher-assisted CPR helps untrained bystanders start compressions; a BLS provider should support and integrate with this system rather than work in isolation.","The recovery link means debriefing the rescuers and supporting the family are part of good resuscitation, not optional extras."],"redFlags":["Failing to activate the emergency response system early — no help or AED is coming if no one calls.","Treating post-ROSC (return of spontaneous circulation) as the finish line and stopping monitoring or care.","A weak first link (delayed recognition) cannot be rescued by a strong later link (excellent ALS)."],"commonMistakes":["Assuming defibrillation is only an advanced-provider skill — AED use is a core BLS and public action.","Confusing the universal chain with the older separate chains; since 2025 there is one six-link chain plus a distinct newborn chain.","Overlooking prevention and surveillance as the leading emphasis for in-hospital arrests."],"memoryAids":["Think 'Call, Push, Shock' for the bystander-dependent front of the chain: activate, compress, defibrillate.","The chain is only as strong as its weakest link — speed and quality at every step.","Recovery = the sixth link; survival is a journey, not a single moment."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"BLS Provider's Priorities Within the Chain","content":"Unresponsive person found\n  → Ensure scene is safe\n  → Check responsiveness and breathing / pulse (≤10 s)\n     → Normal breathing + pulse: monitor, position, reassess\n     → No normal breathing / no pulse: CARDIAC ARREST\n        → Activate emergency response + get AED (Link 1)\n        → Start high-quality CPR immediately (Link 2)\n        → Apply AED and defibrillate as soon as available (Link 3)\n        → Hand off to advanced providers (Link 4)\n        → Support post-arrest and recovery care (Links 5–6)"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary and Systems of Care","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Universal Chain of Survival"]}},"flashcards":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cards":[{"id":"c01_fc01","question":"What is the Chain of Survival?","answer":"A metaphor for the sequence of time-sensitive actions that give a cardiac-arrest victim the best chance of survival, where each link depends on the effectiveness of the ones before it.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc02","question":"How many links are in the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival?","answer":"Six links, in a single chain that applies to adult and pediatric, in-hospital and out-of-hospital cardiac arrest.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc03","question":"List the six links of the 2025 universal Chain of Survival.","answer":"1) Activation of emergency response, 2) High-quality CPR, 3) Defibrillation, 4) Advanced resuscitation interventions, 5) Post-cardiac arrest care, 6) Recovery.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc04","question":"What changed about the Chain of Survival in the 2025 AHA Guidelines?","answer":"The previously separate adult/pediatric and in-hospital/out-of-hospital chains were consolidated into one universal six-link chain, and a separate Neonatal Chain of Care was introduced.","category":"2025 Updates"},{"id":"c01_fc05","question":"Which two links are most influenced by bystanders and BLS providers?","answer":"Early high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation — the interventions most strongly linked to survival.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc06","question":"What is emphasized first in the in-hospital (IHCA) setting?","answer":"Surveillance and prevention — monitoring and rapid-response systems that recognize deterioration early so many arrests are prevented.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc07","question":"What does the recovery link recognize?","answer":"That survival continues beyond return of a pulse; survivors may need rehabilitation, psychological support, and treatment planning, and families need support too.","category":"Recovery"},{"id":"c01_fc08","question":"What is dispatcher-assisted CPR?","answer":"Emergency dispatchers coaching bystanders over the phone to recognize arrest and perform chest compressions before EMS arrives.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc09","question":"Why does early defibrillation matter so much?","answer":"In a shockable rhythm, the chance of survival falls substantially for every minute defibrillation is delayed, so rapid AED use is critical.","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c01_fc10","question":"What is a 'system of care'?","answer":"The coordinated network of people, training, equipment, and organizations that makes each link of the chain function reliably, including quality improvement.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc11","question":"Can a strong later link make up for a weak first link?","answer":"No. Delayed recognition or activation cannot be rescued by excellent advanced care later — the chain is only as strong as its weakest link.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc12","question":"What memory phrase captures the bystander-dependent front of the chain?","answer":"'Call, Push, Shock' — activate emergency response, start compressions, and defibrillate.","category":"Memory Aids"},{"id":"c01_fc13","question":"Which population has its own separate chain in 2025?","answer":"Newborns — the Neonatal Chain of Care, which is distinct from the universal Chain of Survival.","category":"2025 Updates"},{"id":"c01_fc14","question":"What is link 4, advanced resuscitation interventions?","answer":"The advanced care added by trained providers — airway management, medications, and treatment of reversible causes — building on high-quality CPR and defibrillation.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc15","question":"Why are hand-offs important in a system of care?","answer":"Smooth transfer of information and care between bystanders, BLS, and advanced providers keeps interventions continuous and avoids gaps that break the chain.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc16","question":"What is quality improvement's role in the chain?","answer":"Measuring resuscitation performance and feeding it back to responders strengthens the system over time and improves future survival.","category":"Systems of Care"}]}},"quizzes":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","questions":[{"id":"c01_q01","question":"How many links make up the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Four","B. Five","C. Six","D. Seven"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The 2025 Guidelines consolidated the separate adult/pediatric and in-hospital/out-of-hospital chains into a single universal six-link Chain of Survival. A separate seven-step-style Neonatal Chain of Care exists for newborns, but the universal chain itself has six links.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q02","question":"Which change did the 2025 AHA Guidelines make to the Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Removed the defibrillation link","B. Consolidated the separate chains into one universal chain and added a distinct newborn chain","C. Reduced the number of links to four","D. Eliminated the recovery link","E. Made bystander CPR optional"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 update merged the previously separate adult, pediatric, in-hospital, and out-of-hospital chains into a single universal Chain of Survival, and introduced a separate Neonatal Chain of Care for newborns.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q03","question":"Which two interventions, both within BLS scope, are most strongly associated with survival from cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Advanced airway placement and epinephrine","B. Early high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation","C. IV access and 12-lead ECG","D. Targeted temperature management and coronary angiography"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Early bystander CPR and rapid defibrillation are the interventions most strongly linked to survival, and both are core BLS actions available before advanced providers arrive.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q04","question":"In the in-hospital cardiac arrest (IHCA) setting, which emphasis is placed at the front of the system of care?","options":["A. Public-access AED programs","B. Surveillance and prevention with rapid-response systems","C. Bystander recognition by untrained laypeople","D. Dispatcher-assisted CPR"],"correct":1,"rationale":"In hospitals, surveillance, monitoring, and rapid-response systems aim to recognize deterioration early and prevent many arrests before they occur, unlike the bystander-dependent front of out-of-hospital arrest.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q05","question":"What does the recovery link of the Chain of Survival address?","options":["A. Only the immediate minutes after ROSC in the field","B. Physical, cognitive, and emotional rehabilitation and support for survivors and families after arrest","C. Replacing defibrillator pads after use","D. Documentation and billing for the resuscitation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The recovery link recognizes that survival continues beyond return of a pulse; survivors may need rehabilitation, psychological support, and treatment planning, and families need support as well.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q06","question":"A bystander calls 911 and the dispatcher coaches them to push hard and fast on the chest. This is an example of:","options":["A. Advanced cardiac life support","B. Dispatcher-assisted CPR","C. Post-cardiac arrest care","D. The recovery link"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Dispatcher-assisted CPR is when emergency dispatchers coach bystanders over the phone to recognize arrest and begin chest compressions before EMS arrives — a key part of the system of care.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q07","question":"Why is the 'weakest link' concept important in the Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Because only one link needs to work for survival","B. Because a delay or failure in any single link reduces the effectiveness of the entire chain","C. Because advanced care can always compensate for delayed CPR","D. Because the links can be performed in any order"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Each link depends on the ones before it. A weak or delayed link — such as late recognition — cannot be fully rescued by strong later care, so speed and quality matter at every step.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q08","question":"Which of the following is the FIRST link of the universal Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Defibrillation","B. High-quality CPR","C. Activation of the emergency response","D. Post-cardiac arrest care"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Activation of the emergency response is the first link — without calling for help and summoning an AED and advanced providers, the later links cannot occur.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q09","question":"Roughly what happens to survival probability for each minute defibrillation is delayed in a shockable arrest without CPR?","options":["A. It increases","B. It stays the same","C. It falls substantially","D. It is unaffected by time"],"correct":2,"rationale":"In a shockable rhythm, survival probability declines substantially with each minute defibrillation is delayed, which is the rationale for public-access AED programs and rapid AED use.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q10","question":"Which population is served by a separate chain introduced in the 2025 Guidelines?","options":["A. Geriatric patients","B. Newborns (Neonatal Chain of Care)","C. Trauma patients","D. Pregnant patients"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 Guidelines introduced a distinct Neonatal Chain of Care for newborns, separate from the universal Chain of Survival used for other populations.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q11","question":"A patient regains a pulse (ROSC) after CPR and defibrillation. What is the correct BLS mindset?","options":["A. The resuscitation is complete and no further care is needed","B. Continue monitoring and support post-arrest care; recovery is part of the chain","C. Remove the AED pads immediately and reassure the family it is over","D. Stop reassessing because the pulse has returned"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ROSC is not the finish line. Post-cardiac arrest care (link 5) and recovery (link 6) follow; the patient still needs close monitoring, support, and continued care.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q12","question":"Which statement about defibrillation and BLS scope is TRUE?","options":["A. Defibrillation with an AED is exclusively an advanced-provider skill","B. AED use is a core BLS and public-access action available to lay rescuers","C. Only physicians may apply an AED","D. AEDs should only be used after epinephrine is given"],"correct":1,"rationale":"AED use is intentionally designed for lay rescuers and BLS providers. Public-access defibrillation is a cornerstone of the chain and does not require advanced training.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q13","question":"What is the primary purpose of continuous quality improvement within a system of care?","options":["A. To assign blame after unsuccessful resuscitations","B. To measure resuscitation performance and feed it back so future outcomes improve","C. To reduce the number of AEDs in public places","D. To replace bystander CPR with technology"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Quality improvement measures performance (such as compression quality and time to defibrillation) and feeds it back to responders and the system, strengthening the chain and improving future survival.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q14","question":"Link 4 of the universal chain, advanced resuscitation interventions, includes which of the following?","options":["A. Recognizing the arrest","B. Airway management, medications, and treating reversible causes by trained providers","C. Applying the first AED shock","D. Coaching a bystander over the phone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Advanced resuscitation interventions build on high-quality CPR and defibrillation, adding advanced airway management, medications, and treatment of reversible causes delivered by trained providers.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q15","question":"Which sequence best represents a BLS provider's priorities when finding an unresponsive, pulseless adult?","options":["A. Start an IV, then call for help, then compress","B. Activate emergency response and get an AED, start high-quality CPR, defibrillate when available","C. Perform a detailed head-to-toe exam before compressions","D. Wait for advanced providers before doing anything"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The BLS priority sequence is to activate the emergency response and obtain an AED, begin high-quality compressions immediately, and defibrillate as soon as the AED is available — the front links of the chain.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q16","question":"Why did the AHA move from multiple chains to a single universal Chain of Survival in 2025?","options":["A. To make resuscitation harder to teach","B. To simplify and unify the concept across ages and settings while keeping setting-specific emphasis","C. Because defibrillation is no longer recommended","D. To eliminate the role of bystanders"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A single universal chain simplifies teaching and unifies the core sequence across adult, pediatric, in-hospital, and out-of-hospital arrest, while the emphasis (e.g., prevention in hospitals vs. bystander action in the community) still varies by setting.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q17","question":"A hospital rapid-response team is called for a deteriorating patient before any arrest occurs. Which link/emphasis does this represent?","options":["A. Recovery","B. Surveillance and prevention (IHCA emphasis)","C. Defibrillation","D. Post-cardiac arrest care"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Rapid-response and early-warning systems reflect the surveillance-and-prevention emphasis of the in-hospital setting, aiming to prevent arrest by recognizing and treating deterioration early.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q18","question":"Which of the following best describes why public-access AED placement is emphasized?","options":["A. AEDs replace the need for CPR","B. Rapid defibrillation before EMS arrival improves survival in shockable arrests","C. AEDs are only useful in hospitals","D. Public AEDs are meant for training, not real use"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because survival in shockable rhythms declines with each minute of delay, placing AEDs where the public can reach them enables defibrillation before EMS arrives, strengthening a critical link.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q19","question":"The recovery link implies that good resuscitation practice ALSO includes:","options":["A. Stopping all follow-up once ROSC is achieved","B. Supporting survivors and families and debriefing rescuers","C. Avoiding any discussion of the event with the family","D. Immediately discharging the patient"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The recovery link reframes survival as an ongoing journey, so supporting survivors and families and debriefing the rescue team are part of complete, high-quality resuscitation care.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q20","question":"Which statement about the relationship between links is MOST accurate?","options":["A. Links can be skipped without affecting outcome","B. Each link builds on and depends upon the previous links","C. The last link is the only one that matters","D. Bystander links are unimportant if EMS is nearby"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The chain is sequential and interdependent: each link builds on the ones before it, so timely, high-quality performance of the early links sets up the success of the later ones.","difficulty":"Easy"}]}},"scenarios":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cases":[{"id":"c01_s01","title":"Collapse in a Shopping Mall","presentation":"You are a BLS provider walking through a shopping mall when a man in his 60s suddenly collapses. He is unresponsive and not breathing normally. A crowd gathers, and you notice an AED cabinet on the wall about 15 meters away. Two bystanders are nearby.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"Agonal gasps","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"Applying the Chain of Survival, what is the most appropriate immediate set of actions?","options":["A: Direct a bystander to call emergency services and another to bring the AED, and begin high-quality chest compressions now.","B: Wait for EMS to arrive before touching the patient.","C: Perform a detailed head-to-toe assessment before starting CPR.","D: Retrieve the AED yourself first, leaving the patient, before starting any compressions."],"correct":0,"explanation":"The first links of the chain are activation and high-quality CPR. Delegating the call and AED retrieval to bystanders lets you start compressions immediately without leaving the patient, compressing the time to both CPR and defibrillation.","clinicalPearl":"Delegate clearly and specifically ('You, call 911; you, bring that AED') — vague requests to a crowd often go unanswered."},{"id":"c01_s02","title":"Ward Patient Deteriorating","presentation":"On a hospital ward, a monitored patient's early-warning score rises sharply over 20 minutes: increasing respiratory rate, falling blood pressure, and new confusion. The patient still has a pulse and is breathing.","vitals":{"hr":"122 bpm","bp":"88/54 mmHg","rr":"28 bpm","spo2":"90%","loc":"Confused"},"question":"Which system-of-care action best reflects the in-hospital emphasis of the Chain of Survival here?","options":["A: Do nothing until the patient arrests, then start CPR.","B: Activate the rapid-response/medical emergency team to intervene before arrest occurs.","C: Apply an AED to the conscious patient with a pulse.","D: Begin chest compressions immediately."],"correct":1,"explanation":"In-hospital care emphasizes surveillance and prevention. Activating the rapid-response team addresses deterioration early and may prevent the arrest entirely — compressions and AED are not indicated in a patient who has a pulse and is breathing.","clinicalPearl":"The best cardiac arrest is the one that never happens — early-warning systems and rapid-response teams are the prevention link in action."},{"id":"c01_s03","title":"After the Pulse Returns","presentation":"Your team resuscitated a woman in cardiac arrest at home. After several cycles of CPR and one AED shock, she regains a pulse and begins breathing on her own. The family, relieved, asks if everything is 'over now.'","vitals":{"hr":"96 bpm","bp":"104/68 mmHg","rr":"16 bpm","spo2":"94%","loc":"Drowsy, responsive"},"question":"Based on the Chain of Survival, what is the most appropriate next step and message?","options":["A: Tell the family it is over and stop monitoring the patient.","B: Continue close monitoring, support post-arrest care and transport, and explain that recovery is an ongoing process.","C: Remove the AED pads and leave the scene.","D: Discharge the patient at home since she has a pulse."],"correct":1,"explanation":"ROSC is not the end. Post-cardiac arrest care (link 5) and recovery (link 6) continue: the patient needs monitoring, transport, and ongoing care, and the family should understand that recovery is a journey requiring further treatment and support.","clinicalPearl":"Re-arrest is common early after ROSC — keep the AED attached and reassess frequently during transport."}]}},"algorithms":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","algorithms":[{"id":"c01_alg01","title":"Universal Chain of Survival (2025) — BLS Provider View","description":"The 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival unifies adult and pediatric, in-hospital and out-of-hospital cardiac arrest into a single six-link sequence. BLS providers own the earliest, most impactful links.","steps":["Link 1 — Activation of emergency response: recognize cardiac arrest and immediately summon help, an AED, and advanced providers.","Link 2 — High-quality CPR: begin chest compressions right away, pushing hard and fast with full recoil and minimal interruptions.","Link 3 — Defibrillation: apply an AED and deliver a shock as soon as one is available for a shockable rhythm.","Link 4 — Advanced resuscitation interventions: trained providers add airway management, medications, and treatment of reversible causes.","Link 5 — Post-cardiac arrest care: after ROSC, continue monitoring, support oxygenation and circulation, and transport to definitive care.","Link 6 — Recovery: rehabilitation, psychological support, and treatment planning for the survivor and support for the family."]},{"id":"c01_alg02","title":"System-of-Care Emphasis by Setting","description":"The universal chain is applied with different front-end emphasis depending on where the arrest occurs.","steps":["Out-of-hospital (OHCA): emphasize bystander recognition, calling for help, dispatcher-assisted CPR, and public-access AED use before EMS arrival.","In-hospital (IHCA): emphasize surveillance, monitoring, early-warning scores, and rapid-response systems to prevent arrest before it happens.","All settings: deliver high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation, ensure smooth hand-offs between responders, and use quality improvement to strengthen the system.","Newborns: apply the separate Neonatal Chain of Care rather than the universal chain."]}]}},"tables":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","tables":[{"id":"c01_t01","title":"The 2025 Universal Chain of Survival — Six Links","headers":["Link","Name","Primary Owner","BLS Provider Action"],"rows":[["1","Activation of emergency response","Bystanders / first responders","Recognize arrest; call for help and an AED"],["2","High-quality CPR","Bystanders / BLS","Push hard and fast, full recoil, minimal interruptions"],["3","Defibrillation","Bystanders / BLS","Apply AED; shock a shockable rhythm ASAP"],["4","Advanced resuscitation interventions","ALS providers","Support and hand off; assist advanced team"],["5","Post-cardiac arrest care","ALS / hospital team","Monitor, support oxygenation and circulation, transport"],["6","Recovery","Hospital / rehab / family","Support survivorship; debrief and support family"]]},{"id":"c01_t02","title":"OHCA vs IHCA — Where the Emphasis Falls","headers":["Feature","Out-of-Hospital (OHCA)","In-Hospital (IHCA)"],"rows":[["Front-end emphasis","Bystander recognition and action","Surveillance and prevention"],["Who recognizes arrest","Laypeople and first responders","Monitoring systems and staff"],["Key early tools","Dispatcher-assisted CPR, public AED","Early-warning scores, rapid-response teams"],["Goal","Fast CPR and defibrillation before EMS","Prevent arrest before it happens"]]}]}}};
